  },
  {
    question: 'What happens if I fail the FTMO Challenge?',
    answer: 'If you fail by hitting the maximum drawdown or daily drawdown limit, you lose the challenge and the fee paid. However, FTMO offers a Free Retry if you hit the profit target but fail due to other reasons. You can also purchase a new challenge at any time with no waiting period.'
  },
  {
    question: 'How fast are FTMO payouts?',
    answer: 'FTMO processes payouts bi-weekly (every 14 days) after your first month as a funded trader. Most payouts are processed within 1-3 business days via bank transfer, Skrill, or crypto. FTMO has an excellent track record for reliable, on-time payouts.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Is news trading allowed on FTMO?',
    answer: 'Yes, news trading is allowed on FTMO accounts. However, you must be mindful of the 5% daily drawdown rule, as high-impact news events can cause rapid price movements. Many traders avoid trading directly before major announcements to manage this risk.'
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the FTMO discount code?',
    answer: `Use code ${firm.discountCode?.code || 'TRADETHEDAY'} at checkout to receive 10% off your FTMO Challenge fee. This code works on all account sizes from $10K to $200K, saving you between $15 and $108 depending on your chosen account size.`
  }
];

// Schema markup
const breadcrumbSchemaItems = [
  { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
  { name: 'Prop Firms', url: '/propfirms/' },
  { name: 'FTMO Review', url: '/propfirms/ftmo/' }
];

const reviewSchema = generateReviewSchema({
  itemReviewed: {
    type: 'FinancialService',
    name: 'FTMO',
    url: 'https://ftmo.com'
  },
  reviewRating: {
    ratingValue: firm.scores.overall,
    bestRating: 5,
    worstRating: 1
  },
  reviewBody: `Comprehensive review of FTMO prop trading firm. ${firm.scores.overall}/5 rating based on challenge rules, payout reliability, and trader support.`,
  author: 'TradeTheDay Research Team'
});

const faqSchema = generateFAQSchema(faqItems);
const breadcrumbSchema = generateBreadcrumbSchema(breadcrumbSchemaItems);

// Breadcrumb items
const breadcrumbItems = [
  { text: 'Home', href: '/' },
  { text: 'Prop Firms', href: '/propfirms/' },
  { text: 'FTMO Review', current: true }
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title={pageTitle}
  description={pageDescription}
  ogType="article"
  schema={[reviewSchema, faqSchema, breadcrumbSchema]}
>
  <Fragment slot="breadcrumb">
    <Breadcrumb items={breadcrumbItems} />
  </Fragment>

  <!-- HERO SECTION -->
  <section class="review-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="review-hero-content">
        <div class="review-hero-badge">
          <Chip variant="badge" size="sm">Editor's Choice 2026</Chip>
        </div>

        <div class="review-hero-header">
          <div class="review-hero-logo">
            <span class="firm-initial">F</span>
          </div>
          <div class="review-hero-title">
            <h1 class="heading-1">{FIRM_NAME} Review</h1>
            <div class="review-hero-rating">
              <span class="stars">{'‚òÖ'.repeat(Math.floor(firm.scores.overall))}</span>
              <span class="rating-value">{firm.scores.overall}/5</span>
              <span class="rating-count">‚Ä¢ Most Trusted Prop Firm</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="review-hero-tagline">{firm.tagline}</p>

        <div class="review-hero-scorecard">
          {heroScorecard.map((item) => (
            <div class="scorecard-item">
              <span class="scorecard-value">{item.value}</span>
              <span class="scorecard-label">{item.label}</span>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        {firm.discountCode && (
          <div class="review-hero-discount">
            <span class="discount-icon">üéÅ</span>
            <span class="discount-text">
              Use code <strong>{firm.discountCode.code}</strong> for {firm.discountCode.discount}
            </span>
          </div>
        )}

        <div class="review-hero-cta">
          <a href={firm.affiliateUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored" class="btn btn-primary btn-xl">
            Start FTMO Challenge
            <span class="btn-arrow">‚Üí</span>
          </a>
          <a href="#challenges" class="btn btn-secondary btn-xl">
            See Challenge Options
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Navigation links={navigationLinks} />

  <!-- OVERVIEW SECTION -->
  <section id="overview" class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="heading-2">FTMO Overview</h2>
      <p class="body-large">
        FTMO is the world's most trusted proprietary trading firm, having paid out over $200 million to traders since 2015.
        Based in Prague, Czech Republic, they've built an industry-leading reputation for fair rules, reliable payouts, and
        excellent trader support. If you're serious about funded trading, FTMO is the gold standard.
      </p>

      <div class="overview-grid">
        <div class="overview-card">
          <div class="overview-icon">üèÜ</div>
          <h3>Industry Leader</h3>
          <p>9+ years in operation with $200M+ paid to traders. The most established prop firm in the industry.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="overview-card">
          <div class="overview-icon">üí∞</div>
          <h3>Up to 90% Profit Split</h3>
          <p>Start at 80% and scale to 90% through consistent profitability. Keep the majority of what you earn.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="overview-card">
          <div class="overview-icon">üìà</div>
          <h3>Scale to $400K</h3>
          <p>Grow your account through their scaling plan. Double your funding by proving consistent results.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="overview-card">
          <div class="overview-icon">‚ö°</div>
          <h3>Bi-Weekly Payouts</h3>
          <p>Get paid every 14 days via bank transfer, Skrill, or crypto. Fast, reliable withdrawals.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <AnalystNotes
        title="Why FTMO Dominates the Prop Firm Industry"
        icon="üéØ"
        id="overview-notes"
        variant="light"
      >
        <h4>The FTMO Advantage Explained</h4>
        <p>Having analyzed dozens of prop firms over the years, FTMO consistently stands out for one simple reason: they actually pay traders. While competitors have come and gone (RIP MyForexFunds), FTMO has maintained an impeccable track record since 2015.</p>

        <h5>Trust Is Everything in Prop Trading</h5>
        <p>The prop firm industry has a dark side. Many firms are designed to profit from failed challenges, not from funding successful traders. They make rules intentionally difficult, slow-play payouts, or simply disappear with trader funds. FTMO operates differently - their business model depends on funded traders succeeding because they take a cut of profits, not challenge fees.</p>

        <h5>The $200M Payout Milestone</h5>
        <p>FTMO publicly tracks their total payouts - now exceeding $200 million. This isn't marketing fluff; it's verifiable through their published statistics and the thousands of trader testimonials. No other prop firm comes close to this track record. When you pass an FTMO challenge, you know you'll get paid.</p>

        <h5>Real Infrastructure, Real Support</h5>
        <p>FTMO operates from physical offices in Prague with over 100 employees. They have real customer support (responsive within hours, not days), a performance coach for struggling traders, and psychological coaching services. This isn't a fly-by-night operation - it's a legitimate financial services company that happens to fund retail traders.</p>

        <h5>The Challenge Fee Reality</h5>
        <p>Yes, FTMO is more expensive than some competitors. A $100K challenge costs $540 versus $300-400 elsewhere. But consider: would you rather pay $540 with near-certainty of payout, or $300 with uncertainty? The extra cost is insurance against prop firm risk - and in this industry, that insurance is worth every penny.</p>
      </AnalystNotes>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHALLENGES SECTION -->
  <section id="challenges" class="section section--alt">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="heading-2">FTMO Challenge Options</h2>
      <p class="body-large">
        Choose your account size based on your trading experience and goals. All challenges have the same rules -
        only the price and funding amount differ.
      </p>

      <ComparisonTable
        headers={challengeTableHeaders}
        rows={challengeRows}
        caption="FTMO Challenge pricing and requirements for all account sizes"
      />

      <div class="challenge-process">
        <h3 class="heading-3">The FTMO Evaluation Process</h3>
        <div class="process-steps">
          <div class="process-step">
            <div class="step-number">1</div>
            <h4>FTMO Challenge (Phase 1)</h4>
            <p><strong>Target:</strong> 10% profit<br><strong>Time:</strong> 30 days<br><strong>Rules:</strong> Max 10% drawdown, 5% daily drawdown</p>
          </div>
          <div class="process-arrow">‚Üí</div>
          <div class="process-step">
            <div class="step-number">2</div>
            <h4>Verification (Phase 2)</h4>
            <p><strong>Target:</strong> 5% profit<br><strong>Time:</strong> 60 days<br><strong>Rules:</strong> Same as Phase 1</p>
          </div>
          <div class="process-arrow">‚Üí</div>
          <div class="process-step">
            <div class="step-number">3</div>
            <h4>FTMO Trader</h4>
            <p><strong>Profit Split:</strong> 80% (up to 90%)<br><strong>Payouts:</strong> Bi-weekly<br><strong>Scaling:</strong> Up to $400K</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <AnalystNotes
        title="Which Account Size Should You Choose?"
        icon="üí°"
        id="challenge-notes"
        variant="dark"
      >
        <h4>Account Size Strategy</h4>
        <p>The account size you choose should match your trading capital and risk tolerance - not your ego. Here's how to think about it strategically.</p>

        <h5>The Math Behind Account Selection</h5>
        <p>Consider this: a $10K account challenge costs $155. If you pass, you need to make $1,000 (10%) on Phase 1, then $500 (5%) on Phase 2. As a funded trader, you'll keep 80% of profits. To recover your $155 challenge fee, you need to make $194 in profit - just 0.19% of the account.</p>

        <p>For a $100K account ($540 fee), you need $675 profit to break even - 0.068% of the account. Larger accounts are mathematically more capital-efficient if you can afford the challenge fee.</p>

        <h5>Risk Management Consideration</h5>
        <p>With a 5% daily drawdown limit on a $100K account, that's $5,000 maximum daily loss. If your typical trade risks 1%, you can take 5 simultaneous losing trades before hitting the daily limit. On a $10K account, that's only $500 - one bad trade with inappropriate position sizing ends your challenge.</p>

        <h5>Our Recommendation</h5>
        <p>Start with the $25K-$50K range if you're new to prop trading. It's large enough to trade comfortably with proper position sizing but small enough that the challenge fee doesn't create psychological pressure. Once funded, prove yourself, then scale through FTMO's program rather than buying a larger challenge upfront.</p>
      </AnalystNotes>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- RULES SECTION -->
  <section id="rules" class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="heading-2">FTMO Trading Rules</h2>
      <p class="body-large">
        FTMO's rules are designed to identify consistent, disciplined traders - not gamblers. Understanding these rules is
        critical to passing the challenge and staying funded.
      </p>

      <div class="rules-grid">
        <div class="rule-card rule-card--important">
          <div class="rule-icon">‚ö†Ô∏è</div>
          <h3>Maximum Drawdown: 10%</h3>
          <p>Your account equity can never drop more than 10% below your initial balance. On a $100K account, if equity reaches $90,000, you're immediately disqualified. This is calculated on a trailing basis during the challenge.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-card rule-card--important">
          <div class="rule-icon">üìâ</div>
          <h3>Daily Drawdown: 5%</h3>
          <p>Your daily loss cannot exceed 5% of the previous day's ending balance. This resets each day at 5 PM CE(S)T. Hit this limit and you're out - regardless of your overall account status.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-card">
          <div class="rule-icon">üìÖ</div>
          <h3>Minimum Trading Days: 4</h3>
          <p>You must trade on at least 4 separate days during each evaluation phase. This prevents lucky one-trade wonders and ensures you demonstrate consistent trading behavior.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-card">
          <div class="rule-icon">üïê</div>
          <h3>No Time Limit (After Funded)</h3>
          <p>Once funded, there's no profit target or time pressure. Trade at your own pace and withdraw profits bi-weekly. The evaluation phases have time limits (30/60 days).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-card">
          <div class="rule-icon">üì∞</div>
          <h3>News Trading: Allowed</h3>
          <p>You can trade during high-impact news events. However, be mindful of increased volatility and its impact on your daily drawdown limit.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-card">
          <div class="rule-icon">üåô</div>
          <h3>Weekend Holding: Allowed</h3>
          <p>Positions can be held over weekends. Be aware that gaps can occur on market open which could affect your drawdown.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <AnalystNotes
        title="Mastering the 5% Daily Drawdown Rule"
        icon="üéì"
        id="rules-notes"
        variant="light"
      >
        <h4>The Rule That Fails Most Traders</h4>
        <p>The 5% daily drawdown is the number one reason traders fail FTMO challenges. Understanding exactly how it works is essential for survival.</p>

        <h5>How Daily Drawdown Is Calculated</h5>
        <p>At 5 PM CE(S)T each day, FTMO records your account balance (not equity). Your daily drawdown limit for the next 24 hours is 5% below this value. Example: if your balance is $100,000 at 5 PM, your maximum equity cannot drop below $95,000 until the next reset.</p>

        <p><strong>Critical detail:</strong> This includes both realized losses AND unrealized floating losses. An open trade showing -$5,000 floating loss triggers the same breach as a closed -$5,000 loss.</p>

        <h5>The Compounding Trap</h5>
        <p>If you lose money, your daily limit effectively tightens. Start at $100K, lose $3K, end day at $97K. Tomorrow's limit is now $4,850 (5% of $97K), not $5,000. Consecutive losing days quickly compress your available risk.</p>

        <h5>Strategies to Stay Safe</h5>
        <p><strong>Position sizing:</strong> Never risk more than 1% per trade. This gives you 5 consecutive full losses before hitting the daily limit.</p>
        <p><strong>Stop loss discipline:</strong> Always use stop losses. A runaway trade during news or overnight can breach your daily limit before you wake up.</p>
        <p><strong>Time awareness:</strong> Know when the daily reset occurs (5 PM CE(S)T). If you're close to the limit, consider closing positions before reset to start fresh.</p>
        <p><strong>No averaging down:</strong> Adding to losing positions is the fastest way to breach daily drawdown. Cut losses early instead.</p>
      </AnalystNotes>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PAYOUTS SECTION -->
